DIGEST
SB 172 Engrossed 2026 Regular Session Luneau
Present law (R.S. 33:113) provides that a planning commission shall approve or disapprove
a plat within 60 days after the submission thereof to it; otherwise the plat shall be deemed
to have been approved, and a certificate to that effect shall be issued by the commission on
demand.
Proposed law provides that the applicant for a commission's approval may, however, waive
this requirement and consent to an extension of the period. Provides that the disapproval of
any plat shall be stated upon the records of the commission. Any plat submitted to the
commission shall contain the name and address of a person to whom notice of a hearing shall
be sent.
Proposed law retains present law.
Present law provides that a notice of hearing for approval or disapproval of a plat shall be
sent by certified mail of the time and place of the hearing not less than five days before the
hearing date.
Proposed law retains present law.
Present law provides that a planning commission shall give notice of the hearing by at least
one publication in a newspaper of general circulation in the area surrounding the proposed
subdivision, not less than five days prior to the hearing date; provided, however, that in
parishes or municipalities with a population in excess of 150,000, the public hearing may
be waived by the planning commission or planning authority for subdivisions creating five
or less lots not involving the creation of any new streets. Provides further that the provisions
in the waivers shall be clearly set forth in the official subdivision regulations. Proposed law
retains present law but removes the exception for municipalities with a population in excess
of 150,000.
Effective August 1, 2026.
(Adds R.S. 33:113(A) and (B))
